    section.famous-monuments#details
      br
      span.before-hr Famous Monuments
      hr#line
      br
      br
      br
      .swiper-container
        .swiper-wrapper
          .swiper-slide
            img.image-margin(src="http://www.coptic-cairo.com/museum/selection/icons/icons/files/page44-1000-full.jpg" alt="Slide 1")
            .swiper-text
              p St. Barbara is among the most popular Christian saints in the East and West. She was locked in a tower by her pagan father, the rich Dioscuros from Nikomedia While he was travelling, Barbara converted to Christianity and eventually was beheaded by her own father.
          .swiper-slide
            img.image-margin(src="../images/ankh cross.png" alt="Slide 2")
            .swiper-text
              p Coptic gravestones often depict the deceased with their hands raised in prayer. This example was made for a woman who is dressed in a long garment. A traditional Roman mantle covers her head and shoulders and hangs down over her elbows.
          .swiper-slide
            img.image-margin(src="../images/garmnet.png" alt="Slide 3")
            .swiper-text
              p This tunic was a garment commonly worn by males in Greco-Roman civilizations. At the top of this tunic, an arcade encloses figures of dancers and warriors. Below, two vertical panels with warriors and dancers alternate with roundels amid human busts.
          .swiper-slide
            img.image-margin(src="../images/silver casket.png" alt="Slide 3")
            .swiper-text
              p This precious Bible casket of wood is covered with embossed silver sheets attached by nails. A rombic and floral pattern runs along all four sides. In the centre Virgin Mary with Jesus sitting on her lap are placed in between two Arabic lines.
          .swiper-slide
            img(src="http://www.coptic-cairo.com/museum/selection/fresco/files/page27_7.jpg" alt="Slide 3")
            .swiper-text
              p Excavations at the Monastery of St. Jeremiah in Saqqara have yielded several niches that were pierced into the eastern walls of monks’ cells and served the monks for prayer and contemplation. These niches bear christological scenes showing the enthroned Jesus or Jesus Pantocrator. Two niches are decorated with the Virgin Mary nursing the infant Jesus
